******
[1] South Dakota
Date: Fri 23 May 2014
Source: Black Hills Pioneer [edited]
http://www.bhpioneer.com/local_news/article_eac415a6-e290-11e3-9878-001a4bcf887a.html


A "disproportionate number of cases" of pertussis, or whooping cough, in the Black Hills has led officials at a Spearfish medical clinic to stop seeing children for routine well-baby visits.

Dr Angela Anderson, a pediatrician at Spearfish Regional Medical Clinic, said the clinic's staff have diagnosed 10 cases in the past 2 weeks through diagnostic culture and those numbers are expected to rise. "We have been so inundated (with patients showing symptoms) we have cancelled routine well-baby visits," she said. That reason is 2-fold -- to be able to care for those affected and to keep healthy children from being exposed from pertussis.

"We have reorganized our clinic space and staff to handle the influx of patients," she said. "It has been this way for several weeks but increased in severity recently." A diagnostic culture takes 10 days to 2 weeks to receive results. The results go to the state for confirmation. A quicker test, the respiratory DFA [direct fluorescent antibody] test, is done in 2 to 3 days. "Many of the preliminary results are positive for pertussis. Cultures are pending on those," she said.

Anderson said patients who have been exposed and are showing symptoms are being tested and treated. Those who had had been exposed but are not yet showing symptoms are being tested and also treated due to the outbreak. "In all cases, we evaluate the vaccine status for the patient and family members and vaccinate if indicated," she said. "Treatment is antibiotics. You have to be on antibiotics for 5 days before you aren't considered contagious."

The increased number of cases in Spearfish prompted one childcare facility to close its doors until 2 Jun 2014. The board of directors at Children First, in Spearfish, held an emergency meeting where they voted to shut down for the rest of the school year.

Earlier in May 2014, the South Dakota Department of Health released information stating that 23 children had tested positive for the disease. On Wed 21 May 2014, they released data showing 6 more positive cases throughout the state. This is the number confirmed after the local clinics and hospitals sent the positive test results.

"For this time of year to have essentially 30 cases, that's not good for us," said Dr Lon Kightlinger, South Dakota state epidemiologist. "We're taking the opportunity to warn people that pertussis is circulating, especially in some of the Black Hills communities."

In 2013 there were 66 cases reported statewide and 71 cases the year before. In 2010 and 2011 there were 32 and 37 cases reported in the state respectively. More cases are suspected this year [2014] but have yet to be confirmed by a lab diagnosis.

[Byline: Mark Watson]

