[2] California (Sacramento County), nosocomial spread
Date: Fri 23 May 2014
Source: News10 [edited]
http://www.news10.net/story/news/local/south-sacramento/2014/05/24/toddler-contracted-whooping-cough-at-hospital-mom-says/9531047/


It was just a normal trip to the hospital. The mother said her 18-month-old daughter had come down with a mild virus, so she took her to Kaiser Permanente in south Sacramento in mid-to-late April 2014. But, when the child got sicker and sicker, they went back to Kaiser on 12 May 2014. The toddler was coughing uncontrollably and sometimes had difficulty breathing. "I took her there to get better not to get worse," the mother said.

Test results after that visit showed the child had pertussis, also known as whooping cough. "It really scared me. I was at work when I found out," the mother said. "I broke down crying. It terrified me to death." Then the mother discovered an employee at the hospital went to work with pertussis in April 2014 at the same time her daughter was there. She said she believes her little girl contracted the potentially deadly disease at the hospital.

Kaiser Permanente South Sacramento's Chief of Infectious Disease Dr John Belko released the following statement:
"Regarding recent media reports about the ongoing pertussis outbreak in Sacramento County, Kaiser Permanente South Sacramento did recently confirm that an employee, who was vaccinated against the disease, tested positive for pertussis. The employee left work as soon as symptoms appeared and was diagnosed.

"As a precaution Kaiser Permanente is contacting members and employees who may have been exposed to the employee as much as 3 weeks prior to the diagnosis because those infected with pertussis can carry the disease for some time before symptoms appear. Out of an abundance of caution, we are contacting members who may have been exposed between 22 Apr 2014 and 6 May 2014.

As of last week [week of 12 May 2014], the Sacramento County Health Department had 69 confirmed cases of whooping cough. In 2013, there were just 59 cases.

[Byline: Thom Jensen]

